        <h2>What is Plagiarism in Academic Writing and Why Does 
        It Matter?</h2>

        <p>At its core, plagiarism is the act of presenting someone 
        else's work, ideas, data, or words as your own without proper 
        acknowledgment. In university settings, academic misconduct 
        generally falls into several categories:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Direct Plagiarism:</strong> Copying text 
          word-for-word from a source without quotation marks or 
          attribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Self-Plagiarism:</strong> Submitting your own 
          previously graded work for a new assignment without 
          permission.</li>
          <li><strong>Mosaic Plagiarism:</strong> Copying phrases 
          from various sources and patching them together without 
          original synthesis.</li>
          <li><strong>Accidental Plagiarism:</strong> Unintentionally 
          misquoting or forgetting to cite a source due to poor 
          note-taking.</li>
          <li><strong>AI-Generated Plagiarism:</strong> Copying text 
          directly from AI generators like ChatGPT without original 
          analysis or proper citation.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How to Write a Research Paper Step by Step While 
        Maintaining Academic Integrity</h2>

        <p>Learning how to write a research paper step by step 
        involves setting up a systematic workflow. When your writing 
        process is organized, you are much less likely to make 
        careless errors that lead to accidental plagiarism.</p>

        <figure>
          <img
            src="/ThesisArcPro/images/blog/research-paper-writing-step-by-step-flowchart.webp"
