        <h3>Step 1: Formulate a Clear Research Question and 
        Thesis Statement</h3>

        <p>Every successful paper begins with a focused research 
        question. Once you have a research question, develop a clear 
        thesis statement that represents your central argument — the 
        unique claim you will defend using evidence from peer-reviewed 
        literature.</p>

        <h3>Step 2: Use Peer-Reviewed Sources and Academic 
        Databases</h3>

        <p>Rely on established academic databases such as Google 
        Scholar, Scopus, IEEE Xplore, or JSTOR to find peer-reviewed 
        sources. Always note down publication details immediately so 
        you do not lose track of where your information came from.</p>

        <h3>Step 3: Conduct a Systematic Literature Review</h3>

        <p>A literature review is an analytical synthesis that 
        identifies patterns, debates, and gaps in existing research. 
        Group your sources by theme rather than discussing them one 
        by one to maintain an analytical tone and reduce the 
        likelihood of copying descriptive text directly.</p>

        <h3>Step 4: Structuring Your Paper</h3>

        <p>An organized paper structure allows you to present your 
        arguments logically. If you are struggling to map out your 
