              <td>Assessment strategies in universities are undergoing 
              significant revisions due to the rise of artificial 
              intelligence (Author, 2026).</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>2. Use Proper In-Text Citations and References</h3>

        <p>Whether you use APA format, MLA format, or Harvard format, 
        consistency is key. Ensure every source in your bibliography 
        matches an in-text citation in the body of your paper.</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>APA Style:</strong> (Smith, 2023)</li>
          <li><strong>MLA Style:</strong> (Smith 45)</li>
          <li><strong>Harvard Style:</strong> (Smith, 2023, p. 45)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3. Master the Art of Direct Quoting</h3>

        <p>When using a direct quote, enclose the text in quotation 
        marks and include the page number in your citation. Limit 
        direct quotes to no more than 10% of your total paper to 
        ensure your own voice remains dominant.</p>

        <h3>4. Keep Detailed Track of Your Sources</h3>

        <p>Use reference management software like Zotero, Mendeley, 
        or EndNote. Document the author, title, year, journal, and 
        page number of every article you read during your literature 
        search.</p>

        <h3>5. Define Your Own Voice and Arguments First</h3>

        <p>Before you start writing, outline your own arguments and 
        ideas. If you write your draft focusing on your own 
        perspective first, you can then integrate sources to support, 
        challenge, or refine your claims.</p>

        <h3>6. Navigate AI Tools Wisely</h3>

        <p>Use AI only as an assistant for structuring and refining 
        your ideas. Never rely on AI to write entire paragraphs as 
        this introduces risks including hallucinated citations and 
        unoriginal phrasing. Always write the final text yourself.</p>

        <h3>7. How to Write a Research Paper Really Quickly Without 
        Cutting Corners</h3>

        <p>Use the Pomodoro Technique to write in dedicated blocks of 
        time, draft your body paragraphs first before writing the 
        introduction, and keep your references organized from the 
        very beginning. Rushing without a clear structure is one of 
        the main causes of citation mistakes.</p>

        <h3>8. Use a Plagiarism Checker</h3>

        <p>Before submitting your work, run your draft through a 
        reliable plagiarism checker. Take time to address any 
        highlighted areas before submitting the assignment to your 
        instructor.</p>

