        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>How do you write a research paper without 
        plagiarizing?</h3>
        <p>Express others' ideas in your own words through careful 
        paraphrasing, use quotation marks for direct quotes, and 
        provide precise citations for all source material. Keeping 
        careful research notes and organizing your bibliography from 
        the start will help you avoid accidental omissions.</p>

        <h3>What are the 5 C's of academic writing?</h3>
        <p>The 5 C's are Clarity — writing in simple straightforward 
        language. Conciseness — avoiding unnecessary filler words. 
        Coherence — ensuring a logical flow of ideas. Completeness — 
        providing sufficient evidence to support your arguments. 
        Correctness — adhering to proper grammar and academic 
        formatting styles.</p>

        <h3>Is 30% plagiarism too much?</h3>
        <p>In most universities, a 30% similarity score on Turnitin 
        is considered high and will likely trigger a manual review. 
        You should generally aim to keep your non-attributed 
        similarity score as close to 0% as possible. Always check 
        your university's specific guidelines regarding similarity 
        index thresholds.</p>

        <h3>How to avoid plagiarism 5 easy methods?</h3>
        <p>Cite as you write — insert in-text citations immediately. 
        Use quotation marks around any exact wording. Paraphrase 
        completely using your own sentence structures. Track your 
        sources actively as you research. Run a plagiarism detector 
        before final submission.</p>

        <h3>What is the 3 pass method?</h3>
        <p>The 3 pass method is an efficient way to read academic 
        papers. First Pass — read the title, abstract and headings. 
        Second Pass — read the introduction, conclusion and diagrams. 
        Third Pass — read the entire paper deeply to understand the 
        methodology and limitations.</p>

        <h3>How to use ChatGPT without plagiarizing?</h3>
        <p>Treat ChatGPT as a brainstorming assistant rather than a 
        writer. Use it to structure an outline or clarify concepts. 
        Never copy and paste text directly from AI tools and always 
        verify any facts or citations it provides as AI can 
        occasionally generate inaccurate information.</p>

